Getting access to 25k employees details

Hi guys,

I would like to share one of my findings in a private program on HackerOne, which was — simple but critical one. during testing for that private program. I found an endpoint for the Internal team management.

After opening the endpoint (refer the Image above), the only thing running in my mind was “How about I check the directories”. Thus, I immediately utilised Dirsearch to brute force all the directories.

Here is the interesting output.

Noticed? anything?

it’s https://37.--.--.--/register :P

Upon opening register endpoint.

Yuss!!!! Registration page. 😮 anddd….

I tried to register with my details. and.. there was configuration error. I was like…

I tried to register one more time with same email and ended up with an error i.e.

“The email is already registered”

So, I tried to login with my provided credentials anddd…..

Successfully Logged in….

Admin management page.

Typical employee details pages

Disclosed details include Name, Email, Phone-No, Employee ID, Shifts, Reports, Salaries etc.

Sorry, but I needed to hide some details due to confidentiality issues. Some other critical data was disclosing too but don’t have permission to write further.

After verifying the issue I quickly submitted the detailed report to the program via HackerOne. They validated and fixed the issue within few hours.

They permanently fixed the issue by removing the public registration page from the endpoint.

Subsequent to reporting the issue I applied dirsearch on most of the critical endpoints belongs to them however no more endpoint was vulnerable to the same issue.

Timeline.

Report Submitted : 25–10–2017

Report Triaged : 25–10–2017

Initial 1300$ Awarded : 25–10–2017

Report closed as Resolved : 25–10–2017

Final 1200$ Awarded: 26–10–2017

Update

As many people messaging me and asking how I found this Asset/Internal team management endpoint. I am providing info about it here,

I found this endpoint using Github issues conversations.

My recon process.

Tools

Sublister,knockpy,dnsresolver,dirsearch,bucket finder,massdns etc.

After reporting some low hanging issues, I go out and follow engineering/Security teams on Twitter and Github & look for anything interesting

Go through all the issues/Repositories companies engineering team created publicly on Github.

I read all the blog posts by engineering and security team.

I check their DNS every month, They stop using service and forgot to delete CNAMES.

I use their service as user and continue my recon process,

I also use Burp Suite pro history tool to find interesting endpoints.

“Recon is not one time process it’s continuous process“

-Sahil
